<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-25-0424 </DOCNO><TEXT>The development and the current state are outlined of intervening radiology.In this method, various therapeutical operations are carried out underradiodiagnostic control, including catheterizations, the introductionof pace makers and electrodes, biopsy sampling, etc. Using special catheters,the arterial lumen can be widened or the blood supply can be stoppedto a pathological site, an occlusion can be removed, etc. Under angiographycontrol, drugs can be administered locally or foreign bodies removedfrom blood circulation. In many cases, intervening radiology replacessurgical operations and extends the possibilities of surgeons and internalspecialists. (M.D.) 5 figs.</TEXT></DOC>